WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:04.500 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.500 --> 00:00:07.000 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.017 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.017 --> 00:00:11.600 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:16.580 align:middle line:90%
So just to remind you--

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:22.160 align:middle line:90%
so last time, we looked at--

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:26.020 align:middle line:84%
we had the motivating
example that we had a graph.

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:31.840 align:middle line:84%
We had a function f defined
on some interval from a to b.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:35.960 align:middle line:84%
And it was going inside
the real numbers.

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:38.660 align:middle line:84%
And it started
off negative here.

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:40.520 align:middle line:90%
This is f of a.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:42.400 align:middle line:90%
This is negative.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:47.000 align:middle line:84%
And it ended up
positive, f of b.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.880 align:middle line:90%
And we wanted to say--

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:50.510 align:middle line:84%
and this was a
continuous function.

00:00:50.510 --> 00:01:00.950 align:middle line:90%


00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:04.450 align:middle line:84%
And we wanted to say
that there was some c.

00:01:04.450 --> 00:01:16.510 align:middle line:84%
So we wanted to show that
there's a c between a and b

00:01:16.510 --> 00:01:21.170 align:middle line:84%
so that the value
at c is equal to 0.

00:01:21.170 --> 00:01:23.220 align:middle line:84%
So this was the
intermediate value theorem.

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:30.150 align:middle line:90%


00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:38.790 align:middle line:84%
And so this here was
a motivating example

00:01:38.790 --> 00:01:43.810 align:middle line:84%
for trying to understand,
what property of R do we need?

00:01:43.810 --> 00:02:10.650 align:middle line:84%
So what property of R do we
need to make this rigorous?

00:02:10.650 --> 00:02:13.790 align:middle line:84%
So that was the
motivating example.

00:02:13.790 --> 00:02:19.530 align:middle line:84%
And so in order to
make this rigorous,

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:27.050 align:middle line:84%
well, then we need to
concept of that R--

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:31.370 align:middle line:84%
we need to understand
the following statement,

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:42.600 align:middle line:84%
that R is a complete
ordered field.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:46.660 align:middle line:90%


00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:50.610 align:middle line:84%
And a field here--
so just briefly,

00:02:50.610 --> 00:03:07.560 align:middle line:84%
fields here was a set with
two operations, a plus

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:09.820 align:middle line:84%
and what we called
multiplication.

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:16.360 align:middle line:90%


00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:30.130 align:middle line:84%
So each of these two
operations have a 5 property.

00:03:30.130 --> 00:03:36.120 align:middle line:90%


00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:39.040 align:middle line:90%
And then there's an 11 property.

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:47.230 align:middle line:84%
Plus, there's an 11th property
that chain them together.

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:55.950 align:middle line:90%


00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:58.590 align:middle line:84%
And the last one is
usually referred to

00:03:58.590 --> 00:04:00.230 align:middle line:90%
as the distributive law.

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:05.790 align:middle line:84%
So that was one of the
two important concepts

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.790 align:middle line:90%
that we talked about last time.

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:11.030 align:middle line:84%
The other concept
that we talked about

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:13.060 align:middle line:84%
was what's called
an ordered set.

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:18.990 align:middle line:90%


00:04:18.990 --> 00:04:27.030 align:middle line:84%
So that's a set
with an ordering.

00:04:27.030 --> 00:04:30.490 align:middle line:84%
And the ordering has to
have the property that--

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:36.990 align:middle line:84%
so this here, the ordering
has the property--

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:38.770 align:middle line:84%
so it has actually
two properties.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:47.750 align:middle line:90%


00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:49.870 align:middle line:84%
The first one is
that whenever you

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:57.460 align:middle line:84%
take an element x and an
element y in the set, then

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:01.060 align:middle line:84%
you should be able to relate
these two by the ordering.

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:09.740 align:middle line:84%
So either x is equal
to y or x is smaller

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:17.040 align:middle line:90%
than y or y is smaller than x.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:21.580 align:middle line:90%


00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:23.940 align:middle line:84%
And the second
property is what's

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:31.420 align:middle line:84%
called transitive, that if x and
y and c are elements in the set

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:40.580 align:middle line:84%
and x is less than y and
y is less than c, then

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:42.780 align:middle line:90%
x should be less than c.

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:45.740 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
transitive property.

00:05:45.740 --> 00:05:48.300 align:middle line:84%
So the first property,
again, is that you

00:05:48.300 --> 00:05:50.840 align:middle line:90%
can compare any two elements.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:53.880 align:middle line:84%
And the second one is
this transitive law.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:57.800 align:middle line:90%


00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:01.600 align:middle line:84%
So that was the two concepts
we talked about last time.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And then we talked about what
is meant to be an ordered field.

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:17.560 align:middle line:84%
So then we also talked
about ordered fields.

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:23.160 align:middle line:84%
And then ordered fields
is, you have a field that

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:25.440 align:middle line:90%
is also an ordered set.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:33.560 align:middle line:84%
And then the relationship--
so that one being less than

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:34.880 align:middle line:90%
the other one--

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.720 align:middle line:84%
to interact. have So
this is these two things

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:41.680 align:middle line:84%
that, if you take
x is less than y

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:46.080 align:middle line:84%
and you're adding any
elements on both sides,

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:50.350 align:middle line:84%
then it still
preserve the order.

00:06:50.350 --> 00:06:52.110 align:middle line:90%
So this is one thing.

00:06:52.110 --> 00:06:57.310 align:middle line:84%
And the second is that if you
take x that's bigger than 0

00:06:57.310 --> 00:07:04.630 align:middle line:84%
and y that's bigger than 0,
then the product of x and y

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:06.990 align:middle line:90%
should be bigger than 0.

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:10.690 align:middle line:90%
And so this is how the--

00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:15.670 align:middle line:84%
so an ordered field, again,
is a field that has a set,

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:17.830 align:middle line:90%
also has an ordering.

00:07:17.830 --> 00:07:22.750 align:middle line:84%
And then the ordering together
with the operation of the field

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:25.030 align:middle line:84%
should be chained together
by these two rules.

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:27.550 align:middle line:90%


00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:32.770 align:middle line:84%
So we're getting close
to understanding this.

00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:35.370 align:middle line:90%
So this question is--

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:39.750 align:middle line:84%
so in order for all
of this to make sense,

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:45.780 align:middle line:84%
we need to understand what it
means that the real numbers is

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:48.060 align:middle line:90%
a complete ordered field.

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:51.720 align:middle line:84%
And so we have now this part of
it, that it's an ordered field.

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:53.060 align:middle line:90%
We understand that.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:07:58.200 align:middle line:84%
This here, we need to
understand what this means.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:07:58.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:04.380 align:middle line:84%
So now before I get
into that, let's

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:15.760 align:middle line:84%
just talk about-- so
what is the difference

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:24.460 align:middle line:84%
between the real numbers
and the rational numbers?

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:28.420 align:middle line:84%
Remember, the rational numbers
are numbers of this form

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:33.085 align:middle line:84%
here, where this is an integer
and this is a natural number.

00:08:33.085 --> 00:08:37.460 align:middle line:84%
So what is the difference
between these two?

00:08:37.460 --> 00:08:48.200 align:middle line:84%
Well, one difference
is-- so one difference

00:08:48.200 --> 00:09:00.120 align:middle line:84%
is that that square root of
2 is a real number but not

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:00.970 align:middle line:90%
a rational number.

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:13.384 align:middle line:90%


00:09:13.384 --> 00:09:18.650 align:middle line:84%
Now let me try to explain first
why it's not a rational number.

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:21.240 align:middle line:90%


00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:23.560 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to see--

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:25.260 align:middle line:90%
so what is square root of 2?

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:30.600 align:middle line:90%


00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:37.080 align:middle line:84%
The square root of 2, you can
think about it as a number, x.

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:40.520 align:middle line:84%
And it has to have the property
that if you multiply it

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:42.510 align:middle line:90%
by itself--

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:46.550 align:middle line:84%
so x times x or, if
you will, x squared--

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:49.910 align:middle line:90%
this here should be equal to 2.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:51.710 align:middle line:90%
It also should be positive.

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:57.950 align:middle line:90%


00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:04.110 align:middle line:84%
Now suppose-- so I claim
that square root of 2

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:07.010 align:middle line:90%
is not a rational number.

00:10:07.010 --> 00:10:09.050 align:middle line:90%
So by that, I mean that--

00:10:09.050 --> 00:10:12.170 align:middle line:84%
so I want to claim
the following.

00:10:12.170 --> 00:10:17.110 align:middle line:90%


00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:40.600 align:middle line:84%
There does not exist a rational
number x equal to m/n, where--

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:42.740 align:middle line:90%
again, this is an integer.

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:45.240 align:middle line:90%
This is a natural number--

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:53.540 align:middle line:90%
so that x squared is equal to 2.

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:58.780 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that you don't
have a rational number that

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:00.840 align:middle line:90%
is square root of 2.

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:01.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:03.120 align:middle line:90%
Now let's try to prove that.

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:18.500 align:middle line:90%


00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:23.140 align:middle line:84%
So suppose there
was such a number.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:24.540 align:middle line:90%
So we want to prove it.

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:26.240 align:middle line:90%
So we prove by contradiction.

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:36.220 align:middle line:90%


00:11:36.220 --> 00:11:49.180 align:middle line:84%
So assume that there exists
x that is a rational number.

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:50.680 align:middle line:84%
So it can be
written in this form

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:59.200 align:middle line:84%
here, where m is an integer,
and n is a natural number.

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:03.620 align:middle line:84%
So assume that there exists
an x that is a rational number

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:07.080 align:middle line:84%
and so that the
squared is equal to 2.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:10.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, if that's the
case, then m/n--

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:14.140 align:middle line:90%


00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:18.280 align:middle line:84%
so this here squared is
supposed to be equal to 2.

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:21.740 align:middle line:90%


00:12:21.740 --> 00:12:29.720 align:middle line:84%
So this implies that m squared
over n squared is equal to 2.

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:36.550 align:middle line:84%
And this, just multiplying over,
implies that m squared is equal

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:40.750 align:middle line:90%
to 2n squared.

00:12:40.750 --> 00:12:46.050 align:middle line:84%
Now, when we write x as a
rational number-- of course,

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:48.150 align:middle line:84%
we know that there are
many ways of writing it

00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:49.530 align:middle line:90%
as rational number.

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:51.990 align:middle line:84%
Because if you
have one, then you

00:12:51.990 --> 00:12:56.810 align:middle line:84%
can just multiply the
numerator and denominator

00:12:56.810 --> 00:13:01.142 align:middle line:84%
by a natural number, and then
you get another representation.

00:13:01.142 --> 00:13:03.190 align:middle line:90%
But we can assume--

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:05.510 align:middle line:90%
so we may assume.

00:13:05.510 --> 00:13:07.270 align:middle line:90%
So when we have written--

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:23.700 align:middle line:84%
so we may assume that m and n
does not have a common factor.

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:27.950 align:middle line:90%


00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:30.130 align:middle line:84%
Because otherwise, we
could just reduce it.

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:34.230 align:middle line:84%
So we could reduce it until
they don't have a common factor.

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:44.760 align:middle line:90%


00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:45.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:49.780 align:middle line:84%
So we will assume that m and
n do not have a common factor.

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:53.820 align:middle line:84%
We have now that m
squared is equal to this.

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:59.300 align:middle line:84%
But this means that
m here must be even.

00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:08.720 align:middle line:84%
So we have that since m squared
is equal to 2n squared--

00:14:08.720 --> 00:14:13.040 align:middle line:84%
so it means that 2 is
a factor in m squared.

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:15.340 align:middle line:84%
So it must actually
be a factor in m.

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:24.580 align:middle line:84%
So it means that 2
here is a factor in m.

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:27.980 align:middle line:90%
In other words, m is even.

00:14:27.980 --> 00:14:34.946 align:middle line:84%
So you can write m here as 2
times another integer here.

00:14:34.946 --> 00:14:40.730 align:middle line:90%


00:14:40.730 --> 00:14:48.050 align:middle line:84%
But this means that m squared
is equal to 2 m1 squared, which

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:51.640 align:middle line:90%
is equal to 4 m1 squared.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:56.050 align:middle line:84%
And we already know that
that is equal to 2n squared.

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:59.170 align:middle line:90%


00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:03.030 align:middle line:84%
So this means dividing
by 2 on both sides.

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:08.730 align:middle line:84%
It means that 2 m1
squared is equal to n.

00:15:08.730 --> 00:15:12.090 align:middle line:84%
But this means that-- sorry,
is equal to n squared.

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:17.650 align:middle line:84%
So this means that 2 here
must be a factor of n.

00:15:17.650 --> 00:15:29.290 align:middle line:84%
So this means here that
2 is also a factor in n.

00:15:29.290 --> 00:15:33.550 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
this is a contradiction.

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:35.390 align:middle line:90%
So this is a contradiction.

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:41.190 align:middle line:84%
Because now what we have
is that 2 is a factor in m

00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:43.170 align:middle line:90%
and 2 is a factor on n.

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:44.890 align:middle line:90%
So they have a common factor.

00:15:44.890 --> 00:15:46.950 align:middle line:84%
But we assumed they didn't
have a common factor.

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:50.090 align:middle line:90%


00:15:50.090 --> 00:15:52.430 align:middle line:84%
So we argue by
contradiction-- we assumed

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:55.750 align:middle line:84%
there was a rational number
so that the square of it

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:57.230 align:middle line:90%
was equal to 2.

00:15:57.230 --> 00:15:58.990 align:middle line:90%
And we get a contradiction.

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:03.390 align:middle line:84%
So there could not
be a rational number

00:16:03.390 --> 00:16:06.850 align:middle line:84%
that has a property that
the square is equal to 2.

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:10.030 align:middle line:84%
So square root of
2 is definitely

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:11.100 align:middle line:90%
not a rational number.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:18.150 align:middle line:90%


00:16:18.150 --> 00:16:25.230 align:middle line:84%
So now, how do we think
about square root of 2?

00:16:25.230 --> 00:16:34.910 align:middle line:84%
So how do we fit square root
of 2 into the number system?

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:47.060 align:middle line:90%


00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:50.380 align:middle line:84%
Well, square root
of 2 is-- if you

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:55.100 align:middle line:84%
think about it as
a decimal number,

00:16:55.100 --> 00:17:09.859 align:middle line:90%
then it starts with 1.4142136.

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:12.460 align:middle line:90%
And then it continue like this.

00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:18.020 align:middle line:84%
So one way of thinking
about square root of 2

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:20.220 align:middle line:84%
is that it is--
and we'll come back

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:22.460 align:middle line:90%
to this at some later lecture.

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:24.660 align:middle line:90%
So we think about--

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:40.330 align:middle line:84%
so one way of thinking
about square root of 2

00:17:40.330 --> 00:17:47.960 align:middle line:84%
is as a limit of a
sequence of number.

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:52.530 align:middle line:90%


00:17:52.530 --> 00:17:58.530 align:middle line:84%
And that brings us to another
really important concept

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:02.130 align:middle line:84%
that we will talk
much more about later,

00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:06.050 align:middle line:90%
is sequences and limits.

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:10.610 align:middle line:84%
And so if we want to think about
it as a limit of a sequence,

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:14.310 align:middle line:84%
we think about maybe
the number 1 first.

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:16.690 align:middle line:90%
And then we think about 1.4.

00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:30.830 align:middle line:84%
And then we think 1.4.1, and
then 1.414, and then 1.4142,

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:31.710 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:37.230 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this here
is a sequence of numbers.

00:18:37.230 --> 00:18:44.340 align:middle line:84%
And so this is an increasing
sequence of numbers.

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:53.950 align:middle line:90%


00:18:53.950 --> 00:19:02.880 align:middle line:84%
And square root of 2 is
the limit of the sequence.

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:08.270 align:middle line:90%


00:19:08.270 --> 00:19:13.830 align:middle line:84%
So again, we'll talk much more
about sequences and limits

00:19:13.830 --> 00:19:14.330 align:middle line:90%
later.

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:16.710 align:middle line:84%
But this is just
something to keep in mind

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:23.222 align:middle line:84%
as also motivating why we
need to understand sequences

00:19:23.222 --> 00:19:23.930 align:middle line:90%
and their limits.

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:30.620 align:middle line:90%


00:19:30.620 --> 00:19:33.940 align:middle line:90%
So we now know--

00:19:33.940 --> 00:19:37.980 align:middle line:84%
maybe not super surprisingly,
but we know and see

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:43.980 align:middle line:84%
there was a very simple proof
why the real numbers is larger

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:45.420 align:middle line:90%
than the rational numbers.

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:49.100 align:middle line:84%
It contain a particular
square root of 2

00:19:49.100 --> 00:19:53.180 align:middle line:84%
that the rational
numbers does not contain.

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:54.480 align:middle line:90%
We still need to--

00:19:54.480 --> 00:19:58.500 align:middle line:84%
and this is related to
the completeness of R

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:02.520 align:middle line:84%
and why the rational
numbers is not complete.

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:07.220 align:middle line:84%
And this is, again, what
we're now working towards.

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:10.380 align:middle line:84%
So we're working
towards what it means

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:11.970 align:middle line:90%
for a field to be complete.

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:31.570 align:middle line:90%


00:20:31.570 --> 00:20:36.330 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write that,
and I'll explain it more.

00:20:36.330 --> 00:20:46.290 align:middle line:84%
But this here is what we are
aiming towards, completeness,

00:20:46.290 --> 00:20:48.290 align:middle line:84%
which is-- and
I'll explain that--

00:20:48.290 --> 00:20:49.800 align:middle line:84%
at the least upper
bound property.

00:20:49.800 --> 00:21:02.708 align:middle line:90%


00:21:02.708 --> 00:21:03.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:07.110 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take
an ordered set.

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:15.080 align:middle line:90%
So suppose S is an ordered set.

00:21:15.080 --> 00:21:20.160 align:middle line:90%


00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:29.280 align:middle line:84%
And the ordering-- as
usual, we're ordering,

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:33.000 align:middle line:90%
we denote by this.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.460 align:middle line:90%
So suppose S is an ordered set.

00:21:35.460 --> 00:21:40.880 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that A
here is a subset of S.

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:59.328 align:middle line:84%
Then we say that M is an upper
bound for the subset for A

00:21:59.328 --> 00:22:15.280 align:middle line:84%
if, for all elements in A, M
here is bigger or equal to A.

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:19.780 align:middle line:84%
So an upper bound
for a subset is

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:22.540 align:middle line:84%
something that has
to be bigger than all

00:22:22.540 --> 00:22:25.240 align:middle line:84%
the elements in the
subset, bigger or equal to.

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:27.410 align:middle line:84%
It could be equal to
one of the elements.

00:22:27.410 --> 00:22:30.580 align:middle line:90%


00:22:30.580 --> 00:22:32.960 align:middle line:90%
So that's a upper bound.

00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:36.150 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course,
if you look at--

00:22:36.150 --> 00:22:41.140 align:middle line:90%


00:22:41.140 --> 00:22:44.820 align:middle line:90%
so a couple of examples here.

00:22:44.820 --> 00:22:57.580 align:middle line:84%
So if the set here is--
let's say that the set is--

00:22:57.580 --> 00:23:01.660 align:middle line:84%
so S is the natural
numbers here.

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:10.240 align:middle line:90%
And the subset here is 1, 2, 3.

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:20.770 align:middle line:84%
So then the element 4
here is an upper bound

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:38.690 align:middle line:84%
for A. So 4 is an upper bound
for A, whereas 2 is not.

00:23:38.690 --> 00:23:41.090 align:middle line:90%
Obviously, 3 is bigger than 2.

00:23:41.090 --> 00:23:43.240 align:middle line:90%
So 2 is not an upper bound.

00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:48.810 align:middle line:90%


00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:54.170 align:middle line:90%
Another example is if you take--

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:58.010 align:middle line:90%


00:23:58.010 --> 00:24:01.290 align:middle line:84%
let's say S is the
rational numbers,

00:24:01.290 --> 00:24:07.520 align:middle line:84%
and A here is the
natural numbers.

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:14.280 align:middle line:90%


00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:18.070 align:middle line:84%
Then A here does not
have an upper bound.

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:30.240 align:middle line:90%


00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:37.850 align:middle line:84%
And I'll return to this second
example in just a minute.

00:24:37.850 --> 00:24:44.532 align:middle line:90%


00:24:44.532 --> 00:24:49.080 align:middle line:84%
s that is what it means
to be an upper bound.

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:54.840 align:middle line:90%
So now there's another concept.

00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:56.930 align:middle line:90%
And that is a least upper bound.

00:24:56.930 --> 00:25:16.060 align:middle line:90%


00:25:16.060 --> 00:25:19.330 align:middle line:84%
So there's another concept
of the least upper bound.

00:25:19.330 --> 00:25:26.140 align:middle line:90%


00:25:26.140 --> 00:25:30.430 align:middle line:84%
So again, we have S
is an ordered set.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:35.700 align:middle line:90%


00:25:35.700 --> 00:25:43.860 align:middle line:90%
We have A here is a subset of S.

00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:53.340 align:middle line:84%
Then we say that it's a
subset of S. Maybe let me just

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:55.430 align:middle line:90%
point out that it's bounded.

00:25:55.430 --> 00:26:08.890 align:middle line:90%


00:26:08.890 --> 00:26:11.420 align:middle line:84%
So And is a subset
of S that is bounded.

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:14.850 align:middle line:90%


00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:36.770 align:middle line:84%
Then we say that capital
M is a least upper bound

00:26:36.770 --> 00:26:47.570 align:middle line:90%
for a if M is an upper bound--

00:26:47.570 --> 00:26:50.730 align:middle line:90%
so it has to be an upper bound--

00:26:50.730 --> 00:27:02.190 align:middle line:84%
and if, for any
other upper bound--

00:27:02.190 --> 00:27:11.440 align:middle line:90%


00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:14.740 align:middle line:84%
we have to have that for
any other upper bound,

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:25.760 align:middle line:84%
say, M1, we have that M1 has
to be bigger or equal to M.

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:32.080 align:middle line:84%
So a bounded set
has a least upper

00:27:32.080 --> 00:27:38.000 align:middle line:84%
bound if there is an element
that is the smallest, so

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:39.450 align:middle line:90%
to speak, of the upper bound.

00:27:39.450 --> 00:27:42.760 align:middle line:90%


00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:45.035 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:45.035 --> 00:27:53.360 align:middle line:84%
And so now we are ready
to state what it means

00:27:53.360 --> 00:27:55.490 align:middle line:90%
to be a complete ordered field.

00:27:55.490 --> 00:28:03.960 align:middle line:90%


00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:35.340 align:middle line:84%
So a complete ordered
field is an ordered field

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:53.150 align:middle line:84%
so that any bounded subset
has a least upper bound.

00:28:53.150 --> 00:29:03.010 align:middle line:90%


00:29:03.010 --> 00:29:05.782 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:05.782 --> 00:29:08.610 align:middle line:84%
So that's a complete
ordered field.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:11.610 align:middle line:84%
And so we have the
following theorem

00:29:11.610 --> 00:29:15.970 align:middle line:84%
that we're not going to prove
because that really takes us

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:16.720 align:middle line:90%
off field.

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:21.022 align:middle line:90%


00:29:21.022 --> 00:29:22.900 align:middle line:84%
So we'll just take
it for granted.

00:29:22.900 --> 00:29:27.810 align:middle line:90%


00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:53.030 align:middle line:84%
So theorem-- so there exists a
smallest complete ordered field

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:55.020 align:middle line:84%
that contains the
rational numbers.

00:29:55.020 --> 00:30:11.840 align:middle line:90%


00:30:11.840 --> 00:30:12.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:12.340 --> 00:30:13.500 align:middle line:90%
So this is a theorem.

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:17.000 align:middle line:84%
Again, we won't prove
it because it's really

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.300 align:middle line:90%
outside the scope of this class.

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:22.520 align:middle line:84%
It's not really what we
want to focus on here.

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:27.600 align:middle line:90%
But you can prove this.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:41.720 align:middle line:84%
And so that field
is what we call R,

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:43.780 align:middle line:90%
is R. It's the real numbers.

00:30:43.780 --> 00:30:48.800 align:middle line:90%


00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:49.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:49.600 --> 00:30:58.640 align:middle line:84%
So now I want to see that if
we work with that field instead

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:03.630 align:middle line:84%
of the rational numbers, then
actually, we have in particular

00:31:03.630 --> 00:31:07.580 align:middle line:84%
that the square root
of 2 is in that field.

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:25.930 align:middle line:90%


00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:41.640 align:middle line:84%
So we want to show that a square
root of 2 is in the reals.

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:45.246 align:middle line:90%


00:31:45.246 --> 00:31:51.350 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm going to
look at the set A.

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:58.450 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to look
at the set A, which

00:31:58.450 --> 00:32:06.570 align:middle line:84%
is the element in R such
that x here is bigger than 0

00:32:06.570 --> 00:32:13.930 align:middle line:90%
and x squared is less than 2.

00:32:13.930 --> 00:32:17.950 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
look at this set.

00:32:17.950 --> 00:32:23.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, this set
here-- so A here is bounded.

00:32:23.410 --> 00:32:24.270 align:middle line:90%
It's not empty.

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:25.960 align:middle line:90%
We'll say first, it's not empty.

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:29.370 align:middle line:90%


00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:38.090 align:middle line:84%
It's not empty since 1 here
is in A. 1 is positive.

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:44.690 align:middle line:84%
And 1 squared here is, of
course, 1, which is less than 2.

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:46.450 align:middle line:90%
So it's non-empty.

00:32:46.450 --> 00:32:50.460 align:middle line:90%
And A here is also A is bounded.

00:32:50.460 --> 00:32:53.970 align:middle line:90%


00:32:53.970 --> 00:33:09.480 align:middle line:84%
Because any element-- so for all
x in A, you have that x squared,

00:33:09.480 --> 00:33:12.360 align:middle line:84%
x is positive and
is less than 2.

00:33:12.360 --> 00:33:17.320 align:middle line:84%
So this means that x here
must be itself less than 2.

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:20.980 align:middle line:84%
Because 2, of course, when you
square it, you're getting 4.

00:33:20.980 --> 00:33:25.760 align:middle line:90%


00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:30.010 align:middle line:84%
So A here is a bounded
subset of the reals.

00:33:30.010 --> 00:33:40.600 align:middle line:90%


00:33:40.600 --> 00:33:45.130 align:middle line:84%
So now the real has the
least upper bound property.

00:33:45.130 --> 00:33:47.960 align:middle line:90%


00:33:47.960 --> 00:33:51.720 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
I can now define--

00:33:51.720 --> 00:34:03.015 align:middle line:84%
so define square root of 2
to be the least upper bound.

00:34:03.015 --> 00:34:20.030 align:middle line:84%
So define it to be the
least upper bound of A. A

00:34:20.030 --> 00:34:23.429 align:middle line:90%
was a nonempty bounded subset.

00:34:23.429 --> 00:34:29.350 align:middle line:84%
So because we are in the reals,
if you grant this theorem,

00:34:29.350 --> 00:34:30.970 align:middle line:84%
then there is a
least upper bound.

00:34:30.970 --> 00:34:34.790 align:middle line:90%


00:34:34.790 --> 00:34:38.550 align:middle line:90%
So now let's denote--

00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:56.010 align:middle line:84%
so let me denote
this number by x.

00:34:56.010 --> 00:34:58.910 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to denoted by x
instead of square root of 2.

00:34:58.910 --> 00:35:02.090 align:middle line:84%
Because if I denote it
by square root of 2,

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:03.810 align:middle line:90%
then it's going to be confusing.

00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:07.010 align:middle line:84%
And it's like you
will automatically

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:11.290 align:middle line:84%
use what you think square
root 2 should satisfy.

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:17.175 align:middle line:90%
So let's call it x.

00:35:17.175 --> 00:35:20.570 align:middle line:90%


00:35:20.570 --> 00:35:23.870 align:middle line:90%
So I want to prove--

00:35:23.870 --> 00:35:41.528 align:middle line:84%
so it's clear that since x here
is at least upper bound for A

00:35:41.528 --> 00:35:45.890 align:middle line:84%
and, in particular,
1 is in A, then

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:51.120 align:middle line:84%
it means that 1 here has to
be less than or equal to x.

00:35:51.120 --> 00:35:54.760 align:middle line:90%
And 1, of course, is positive.

00:35:54.760 --> 00:36:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So it means that x here
is definitely positive.

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:04.610 align:middle line:84%
Now we need to show
that the square--

00:36:04.610 --> 00:36:13.840 align:middle line:90%


00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:31.480 align:middle line:84%
so we need to show that
x squared is equal to 2.

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:33.320 align:middle line:84%
That's what we need
to prove in order

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:36.580 align:middle line:84%
to prove that x is really
the square root of 2.

00:36:36.580 --> 00:36:39.406 align:middle line:90%


00:36:39.406 --> 00:36:41.380 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to divide it up.

00:36:41.380 --> 00:36:51.520 align:middle line:84%
So we divide the
proof into two steps.

00:36:51.520 --> 00:37:02.390 align:middle line:90%


00:37:02.390 --> 00:37:06.810 align:middle line:84%
The first one is
that we want to--

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:14.830 align:middle line:84%
so step 1, we're going to show
that x squared is less than

00:37:14.830 --> 00:37:16.790 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 2.

00:37:16.790 --> 00:37:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we would
show in the first step.

00:37:19.470 --> 00:37:22.750 align:middle line:84%
And then the second step would
be the reverse inequality.

00:37:22.750 --> 00:37:24.930 align:middle line:84%
And of course, together,
this would be the proof.

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:28.190 align:middle line:90%


00:37:28.190 --> 00:37:34.210 align:middle line:84%
So again, just like we
argued before, in this case,

00:37:34.210 --> 00:37:36.450 align:middle line:84%
we will also argue
by contradiction.

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:39.390 align:middle line:90%


00:37:39.390 --> 00:37:41.590 align:middle line:84%
You may get the feeling
that we're always

00:37:41.590 --> 00:37:43.930 align:middle line:84%
going to argue by
contradiction in this class.

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:45.110 align:middle line:90%
And we won't.

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:49.290 align:middle line:84%
And it's generally thought
of that it's better style

00:37:49.290 --> 00:37:51.290 align:middle line:90%
to prove things directly.

00:37:51.290 --> 00:37:55.050 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes it's
a much more logical

00:37:55.050 --> 00:37:58.730 align:middle line:84%
and easier in a way-- at
least, easier the first time--

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:00.270 align:middle line:90%
to prove it by contradiction.

00:38:00.270 --> 00:38:03.970 align:middle line:84%
And there's nothing wrong with
proving it by contradiction.

00:38:03.970 --> 00:38:06.390 align:middle line:84%
So we will show this
by contradiction.

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:20.150 align:middle line:90%


00:38:20.150 --> 00:38:20.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:20.650 --> 00:38:50.000 align:middle line:90%


00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:51.820 align:middle line:84%
So we show this
by contradiction.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:53.500 align:middle line:90%
And so we assume first--

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:56.300 align:middle line:90%
so assume not.

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:59.760 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:05.260 align:middle line:84%
So assume that x squared is
not less than or equal to 2.

00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:06.360 align:middle line:90%
So we assume not.

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:09.160 align:middle line:90%


00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:17.980 align:middle line:84%
So assume that x squared
is strictly bigger than 2.

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:20.720 align:middle line:90%


00:39:20.720 --> 00:39:26.440 align:middle line:84%
Now I will look at x
minus some small number.

00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:29.200 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
eventually prove

00:39:29.200 --> 00:39:34.100 align:middle line:84%
that if I'm looking at x
minus some small number--

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:39.400 align:middle line:90%


00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:42.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to prove now that if
this here was strictly bigger

00:39:42.510 --> 00:39:46.910 align:middle line:84%
than 2, then I can find some
small number so that this here

00:39:46.910 --> 00:39:48.770 align:middle line:90%
would also be an upper bound.

00:39:48.770 --> 00:39:53.710 align:middle line:90%
So h would be positive.

00:39:53.710 --> 00:39:56.870 align:middle line:84%
This here would be a number
strictly less than x.

00:39:56.870 --> 00:39:59.890 align:middle line:84%
And I would show that this
here is also an upper bound.

00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:02.142 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to do.

00:40:02.142 --> 00:40:09.750 align:middle line:84%
So I take x minus
h, and I square it.

00:40:09.750 --> 00:40:21.790 align:middle line:84%
If I do that, then I get that
this is x squared minus 2xh plus

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:24.630 align:middle line:90%
h squared.

00:40:24.630 --> 00:40:27.050 align:middle line:90%
The squared is non-negative.

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:31.590 align:middle line:84%
So this here is definitely
bigger or equal to x squared

00:40:31.590 --> 00:40:33.394 align:middle line:90%
minus 2xh.

00:40:33.394 --> 00:40:37.030 align:middle line:90%


00:40:37.030 --> 00:40:38.770 align:middle line:90%
And so you see that--

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:39.270 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:40:39.270 --> 00:40:52.280 align:middle line:90%


00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:56.980 align:middle line:84%
So we have that x
squared is bigger than 2.

00:40:56.980 --> 00:41:04.280 align:middle line:84%
So this means that x
squared minus 2 is positive.

00:41:04.280 --> 00:41:06.520 align:middle line:84%
I'm just subtracting
a 2 from both sides.

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:10.260 align:middle line:84%
So we're assuming that
this here is positive.

00:41:10.260 --> 00:41:13.340 align:middle line:90%


00:41:13.340 --> 00:41:16.870 align:middle line:84%
And so now if I just
make sure that--

00:41:16.870 --> 00:41:23.780 align:middle line:90%


00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:27.380 align:middle line:90%
so now I'm going to choose.

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:28.760 align:middle line:90%
So I want to choose.

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:31.600 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove
that x minus--

00:41:31.600 --> 00:41:33.540 align:middle line:90%
so I want to show--

00:41:33.540 --> 00:41:46.920 align:middle line:84%
so I want to get
the contradiction

00:41:46.920 --> 00:42:04.960 align:middle line:84%
by finding a h bigger than
0 so that minus h is also

00:42:04.960 --> 00:42:11.720 align:middle line:90%
an upper bound for A.

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:16.060 align:middle line:84%
Because this here is clearly
smaller than x, right?

00:42:16.060 --> 00:42:18.280 align:middle line:84%
And this would then
contradict that x

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:20.840 align:middle line:90%
was the smallest upper bound.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:23.840 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I want to do.

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:29.120 align:middle line:90%
And so now, how do I do that?

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:31.190 align:middle line:84%
So using this little
calculation here--

00:42:31.190 --> 00:42:34.680 align:middle line:90%


00:42:34.680 --> 00:42:36.950 align:middle line:90%
so what I want to do is--

00:42:36.950 --> 00:42:50.390 align:middle line:84%
so I want to find h
positive so that when

00:42:50.390 --> 00:42:55.170 align:middle line:84%
I square, when I subtract
h from x and I square it,

00:42:55.170 --> 00:42:59.030 align:middle line:84%
then I still get
something bigger than 2.

00:42:59.030 --> 00:43:05.070 align:middle line:84%
So I want to find h positive
so that this thing here

00:43:05.070 --> 00:43:08.390 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than 2.

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:13.310 align:middle line:84%
And all I need to do is, I
need to show that I can find h

00:43:13.310 --> 00:43:28.390 align:middle line:84%
so that this thing here-- so
enough to show that I can find h

00:43:28.390 --> 00:43:36.940 align:middle line:84%
such that x squared minus 2xh,
that this thing here is bigger

00:43:36.940 --> 00:43:37.520 align:middle line:90%
than 2.

00:43:37.520 --> 00:43:41.060 align:middle line:90%


00:43:41.060 --> 00:43:44.580 align:middle line:84%
And so you see, now
I just move over

00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:48.820 align:middle line:84%
on the other side to say that
this here is bigger than 2.

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:51.700 align:middle line:84%
It's the same as saying I
can just move this 2 over

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:54.540 align:middle line:90%
on that side.

00:43:54.540 --> 00:43:57.180 align:middle line:84%
And I can move this here
over on the other side.

00:43:57.180 --> 00:44:03.860 align:middle line:84%
So I just need to find
h with this property.

00:44:03.860 --> 00:44:10.180 align:middle line:84%
But that, of course, is
equivalent to saying that h has

00:44:10.180 --> 00:44:17.060 align:middle line:84%
to be less than x
squared minus 2 over 2x.

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:18.980 align:middle line:90%
x is positive.

00:44:18.980 --> 00:44:21.500 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is
strictly positive.

00:44:21.500 --> 00:44:24.120 align:middle line:84%
So I can certainly
find a positive number.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.460 align:middle line:84%
This here is something
strictly positive.

00:44:26.460 --> 00:44:30.140 align:middle line:84%
So I can certainly
find some small h

00:44:30.140 --> 00:44:32.910 align:middle line:84%
so that it's less than this
strictly positive number.

00:44:32.910 --> 00:44:35.960 align:middle line:90%


00:44:35.960 --> 00:44:39.200 align:middle line:90%
So this is step one.

00:44:39.200 --> 00:44:42.660 align:middle line:84%
This is just showing that
x squared was less than

00:44:42.660 --> 00:44:44.360 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 2.

00:44:44.360 --> 00:44:52.320 align:middle line:84%
Now I want to argue similarly
to prove the other direction.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:45:15.900 align:middle line:90%


00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:18.800 align:middle line:84%
In this case, there's not
really any difference.

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:23.600 align:middle line:84%
You see in a minute that
the one inequality is not

00:45:23.600 --> 00:45:25.460 align:middle line:90%
any easier than the other.

00:45:25.460 --> 00:45:28.180 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.180 --> 00:45:29.760 align:middle line:90%
I have a colleague here.

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:31.550 align:middle line:90%
He's is retired now.

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:34.430 align:middle line:84%
And he collaborated
with some other guy

00:45:34.430 --> 00:45:37.250 align:middle line:90%
and made a lot of famous work.

00:45:37.250 --> 00:45:40.270 align:middle line:84%
And the other guy maybe
become even more famous.

00:45:40.270 --> 00:45:42.853 align:middle line:84%
And he used to say that
when you do mathematics--

00:45:42.853 --> 00:45:45.270 align:middle line:84%
so it doesn't really apply
here because the two inequality

00:45:45.270 --> 00:45:46.590 align:middle line:90%
is just as easy.

00:45:46.590 --> 00:45:50.470 align:middle line:84%
But he used to say that
when you do mathematics,

00:45:50.470 --> 00:45:52.230 align:middle line:90%
there's three things you do.

00:45:52.230 --> 00:45:54.150 align:middle line:90%
You locate a problem.

00:45:54.150 --> 00:45:58.110 align:middle line:84%
You prove one of the two
inequality, whichever

00:45:58.110 --> 00:45:59.590 align:middle line:90%
one is easier.

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:00.810 align:middle line:90%
And you ask Raghu--

00:46:00.810 --> 00:46:03.460 align:middle line:84%
Raghu was his collaborator--
to prove the other inequality.

00:46:03.460 --> 00:46:05.778 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:05.778 --> 00:46:07.510 align:middle line:90%


00:46:07.510 --> 00:46:08.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:08.010 --> 00:46:15.430 align:middle line:90%


00:46:15.430 --> 00:46:22.950 align:middle line:84%
So step two is that x squared
is bigger or equal to 2.

00:46:22.950 --> 00:46:26.010 align:middle line:90%
And we will again prove this.

00:46:26.010 --> 00:46:36.401 align:middle line:84%
So again, we'll show
this by contradiction.

00:46:36.401 --> 00:46:43.926 align:middle line:90%


00:46:43.926 --> 00:46:50.340 align:middle line:90%
So I assume not.

00:46:50.340 --> 00:47:01.640 align:middle line:84%
So assume that x squared here
is strictly smaller than 2.

00:47:01.640 --> 00:47:04.460 align:middle line:90%


00:47:04.460 --> 00:47:06.900 align:middle line:90%
Now what we want to prove is--

00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:12.140 align:middle line:84%
so then we want to
get the contradiction.

00:47:12.140 --> 00:47:36.330 align:middle line:84%
We want to get the contradiction
by showing that x is not

00:47:36.330 --> 00:47:46.930 align:middle line:84%
an upper bound, an
upper bound for A. x

00:47:46.930 --> 00:47:49.850 align:middle line:84%
was supposed to be the least
upper bound, so in particular

00:47:49.850 --> 00:47:52.718 align:middle line:90%
an upper bound.

00:47:52.718 --> 00:47:54.730 align:middle line:90%
So how do we do that?

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:59.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, we're going to add
just a little bit to x.

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:02.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is similar to
how we argued before.

00:48:02.380 --> 00:48:14.570 align:middle line:90%


00:48:14.570 --> 00:48:19.930 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to add--

00:48:19.930 --> 00:48:24.070 align:middle line:90%
so h, again, is being positive.

00:48:24.070 --> 00:48:26.550 align:middle line:90%
So h is positive.

00:48:26.550 --> 00:48:30.590 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to add
just a little bit to x.

00:48:30.590 --> 00:48:38.030 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to see that
if I choose h small, then

00:48:38.030 --> 00:48:46.890 align:middle line:84%
I can find something in the
set if I choose it so that x--

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:50.850 align:middle line:84%
so I want to prove that
if h is small enough,

00:48:50.850 --> 00:48:57.390 align:middle line:84%
then x plus h is
in A, contradicting

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:00.710 align:middle line:90%
that x was an upper bound.

00:49:00.710 --> 00:49:03.690 align:middle line:84%
And so h is going
to be chosen small.

00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:08.710 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, it's
going to be between 0 and 1.

00:49:08.710 --> 00:49:13.070 align:middle line:90%
And I'm looking at x plus h.

00:49:13.070 --> 00:49:14.750 align:middle line:90%
And I'm squaring it.

00:49:14.750 --> 00:49:19.815 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is x squared
plus h squared plus 2hx.

00:49:19.815 --> 00:49:23.100 align:middle line:90%


00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:27.620 align:middle line:90%
Now h is less than 1.

00:49:27.620 --> 00:49:34.100 align:middle line:84%
So this means that h
squared-- since h is positive

00:49:34.100 --> 00:49:40.780 align:middle line:84%
and is less than 1, then
you have that h squared

00:49:40.780 --> 00:49:46.420 align:middle line:90%
is less than actual h.

00:49:46.420 --> 00:50:00.460 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing here is less
than x squared plus h plus 2hx

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:02.350 align:middle line:90%
And I want to show--

00:50:02.350 --> 00:50:05.920 align:middle line:90%


00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:12.100 align:middle line:84%
so I want to show that this
x plus h, this is still in A.

00:50:12.100 --> 00:50:33.650 align:middle line:84%
So I want to show that we can
find such a h so that this here

00:50:33.650 --> 00:50:37.070 align:middle line:90%
squared is still less than 2.

00:50:37.070 --> 00:50:39.650 align:middle line:90%


00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:43.410 align:middle line:84%
So all I need to do is,
because of this inequality,

00:50:43.410 --> 00:50:47.650 align:middle line:84%
I just need to find an h so that
this thing here is less than 2.

00:50:47.650 --> 00:51:06.550 align:middle line:84%
So I want to find h such that
this thing here is less than 2.

00:51:06.550 --> 00:51:22.670 align:middle line:90%


00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:27.090 align:middle line:84%
Right now, again, we're just
moving over on the other side.

00:51:27.090 --> 00:51:29.870 align:middle line:84%
In this case, we're moving
this x squared over here.

00:51:29.870 --> 00:51:35.250 align:middle line:84%
So we have h plus
2hx is less than--

00:51:35.250 --> 00:51:38.790 align:middle line:90%
this is what we want to find--

00:51:38.790 --> 00:51:48.110 align:middle line:84%
want to find an h such that
this thing here is less than 2

00:51:48.110 --> 00:51:50.310 align:middle line:90%
minus a x squared.

00:51:50.310 --> 00:51:53.270 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is
now-- because x squared

00:51:53.270 --> 00:51:54.570 align:middle line:90%
is strictly less than 2.

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:57.070 align:middle line:90%
This is positive.

00:51:57.070 --> 00:52:00.990 align:middle line:84%
Here, you can just
factor out an h.

00:52:00.990 --> 00:52:03.030 align:middle line:84%
So if you factor
out an h, then you

00:52:03.030 --> 00:52:09.670 align:middle line:84%
have this thing here is
less than 2 minus x squared.

00:52:09.670 --> 00:52:13.190 align:middle line:84%
And this is just saying that you
want to find an h so that this

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:20.940 align:middle line:84%
thing here is strictly less than
2 minus x squared over 1 plus

00:52:20.940 --> 00:52:22.320 align:middle line:90%
2x.

00:52:22.320 --> 00:52:24.460 align:middle line:90%
x is positive.

00:52:24.460 --> 00:52:27.740 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here is positive.

00:52:27.740 --> 00:52:29.960 align:middle line:84%
So this and this here
is also positive.

00:52:29.960 --> 00:52:31.520 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a
positive number.

00:52:31.520 --> 00:52:35.060 align:middle line:84%
So you can definitely find
some x with this property.

00:52:35.060 --> 00:52:36.840 align:middle line:90%
And then you see that--

00:52:36.840 --> 00:52:41.980 align:middle line:84%
so this means that this x plus
h would also be in the set a,

00:52:41.980 --> 00:52:44.440 align:middle line:84%
contradicting that x
was an upper bound.

00:52:44.440 --> 00:52:52.140 align:middle line:90%


00:52:52.140 --> 00:52:52.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:52.640 --> 00:52:54.900 align:middle line:84%
So now, accordingly,
we immediately

00:52:54.900 --> 00:53:07.200 align:middle line:84%
get of this is that the
rationals is not complete.

00:53:07.200 --> 00:53:10.560 align:middle line:84%
So we get the
following corollarys.

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:16.450 align:middle line:90%


00:53:16.450 --> 00:53:18.300 align:middle line:84%
The rational number
is not complete.

00:53:18.300 --> 00:53:26.010 align:middle line:90%


00:53:26.010 --> 00:53:27.550 align:middle line:90%
And this is just because--

00:53:27.550 --> 00:53:31.350 align:middle line:84%
so the proof of that is
that we have already--

00:53:31.350 --> 00:53:43.150 align:middle line:84%
so if we're looking at a field
that is complete and contains

00:53:43.150 --> 00:53:46.170 align:middle line:84%
a rational, then we know
that square root of 2

00:53:46.170 --> 00:53:47.970 align:middle line:90%
is in that field.

00:53:47.970 --> 00:54:08.250 align:middle line:84%
So we just proven that if f
is a complete field containing

00:54:08.250 --> 00:54:23.630 align:middle line:84%
the rationals, then square
root of 2 is in that field.

00:54:23.630 --> 00:54:40.030 align:middle line:84%
But we have also shown
that square root of 2

00:54:40.030 --> 00:54:42.290 align:middle line:90%
is not a rational number.

00:54:42.290 --> 00:54:46.930 align:middle line:90%


00:54:46.930 --> 00:54:49.510 align:middle line:84%
So the rational in
itself is not complete.

00:54:49.510 --> 00:54:54.710 align:middle line:90%


00:54:54.710 --> 00:54:56.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:56.420 --> 00:55:00.150 align:middle line:84%
Now the next thing
I want to do is

00:55:00.150 --> 00:55:03.670 align:middle line:84%
prove what's called the
Archimedean property,

00:55:03.670 --> 00:55:05.990 align:middle line:90%
the Archimedean property.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:07.750 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
actually something

00:55:07.750 --> 00:55:15.280 align:middle line:84%
that was sort of used here, sort
of used it a little bit already.

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:20.100 align:middle line:84%
But let me just
prove it rigorously.

00:55:20.100 --> 00:55:28.740 align:middle line:90%


00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:30.920 align:middle line:90%
So the Archimedean property--

00:55:30.920 --> 00:55:41.140 align:middle line:90%


00:55:41.140 --> 00:55:55.260 align:middle line:84%
so this is the following, that
for all real numbers, every time

00:55:55.260 --> 00:56:07.050 align:middle line:84%
you take a real number, then
there exists an integer--

00:56:07.050 --> 00:56:11.450 align:middle line:90%


00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:25.370 align:middle line:84%
actually, even a natural
number n such that n here

00:56:25.370 --> 00:56:28.130 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than x.

00:56:28.130 --> 00:56:28.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:31.490 align:middle line:84%
This seems like a
kind of trivial fact.

00:56:31.490 --> 00:56:35.917 align:middle line:84%
But let me try to actually
prove it in a rigorous way.

00:56:35.917 --> 00:56:38.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is what's called
the Archimedean property.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:43.610 align:middle line:90%


00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:48.590 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, we prove
this by contradiction.

00:56:48.590 --> 00:56:56.770 align:middle line:90%


00:56:56.770 --> 00:57:09.960 align:middle line:84%
So suppose not-- so if there
existed an x so that you did not

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:17.800 align:middle line:84%
have this, well then--
so suppose not, then--

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:19.560 align:middle line:84%
so the negation
of that statement

00:57:19.560 --> 00:57:29.120 align:middle line:84%
is that then there
exists an x such that

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:36.520 align:middle line:84%
for all natural
numbers, for all,

00:57:36.520 --> 00:57:40.520 align:middle line:84%
you have that n here is
less than or equal to x.

00:57:40.520 --> 00:57:43.880 align:middle line:90%


00:57:43.880 --> 00:57:45.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's actually equal to x.

00:57:45.720 --> 00:57:50.320 align:middle line:84%
Because this is the
negation of that.

00:57:50.320 --> 00:58:02.350 align:middle line:84%
But this means that x
here is an upper bound.

00:58:02.350 --> 00:58:09.030 align:middle line:90%


00:58:09.030 --> 00:58:16.780 align:middle line:90%
And so then you could take--

00:58:16.780 --> 00:58:21.390 align:middle line:84%
so you could replace by the
least upper bound property.

00:58:21.390 --> 00:58:23.900 align:middle line:90%


00:58:23.900 --> 00:58:25.200 align:middle line:90%
So it's upper bound.

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:34.340 align:middle line:84%
So in particular,
the natural number

00:58:34.340 --> 00:58:45.340 align:middle line:84%
is a bounded subset
of the reals.

00:58:45.340 --> 00:58:50.340 align:middle line:84%
And then you could
take-- so then we let,

00:58:50.340 --> 00:59:10.030 align:middle line:84%
let's say, y be the least upper
bound of the natural numbers.

00:59:10.030 --> 00:59:12.690 align:middle line:84%
If the natural numbers
was really bounded,

00:59:12.690 --> 00:59:14.630 align:middle line:84%
because it's a
subset of the reals,

00:59:14.630 --> 00:59:17.510 align:middle line:84%
we could now take the
least upper bound.

00:59:17.510 --> 00:59:18.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:18.010 --> 00:59:21.370 align:middle line:84%
So now what we have
is that we have

00:59:21.370 --> 00:59:26.630 align:middle line:90%
that for any natural number--

00:59:26.630 --> 00:59:38.070 align:middle line:84%
so for all, we have that n here
is less than or equal to y.

00:59:38.070 --> 00:59:40.410 align:middle line:84%
But whenever you take
a natural number,

00:59:40.410 --> 00:59:44.250 align:middle line:84%
then add 1 to that
natural number--

00:59:44.250 --> 00:59:48.110 align:middle line:90%
so we would also have that--

00:59:48.110 --> 00:59:52.730 align:middle line:90%


00:59:52.730 --> 00:59:57.770 align:middle line:84%
so y is not just an upper
bound for n, but it actually--

00:59:57.770 --> 01:00:00.950 align:middle line:84%
because n plus 1 is also
not a natural number.

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:05.680 align:middle line:84%
So y here would have to be
bigger or equal to n plus 1

01:00:05.680 --> 01:00:07.880 align:middle line:90%
also.

01:00:07.880 --> 01:00:10.120 align:middle line:90%
And this now holds for all n.

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:14.420 align:middle line:84%
So this means that-- just moving
the 1 over on the other side--

01:00:14.420 --> 01:00:22.240 align:middle line:84%
so hence, n here is
less than y minus 1.

01:00:22.240 --> 01:00:34.080 align:middle line:84%
But this here say that-- so
this means that y minus 1

01:00:34.080 --> 01:00:49.980 align:middle line:84%
is also an upper bound and
that this is a contradiction.

01:00:49.980 --> 01:00:55.910 align:middle line:84%
So this contradicts that y
was the least upper bound.

01:00:55.910 --> 01:01:04.500 align:middle line:90%


01:01:04.500 --> 01:01:06.150 align:middle line:84%
And that's the
Archimedean property.

01:01:06.150 --> 01:01:08.700 align:middle line:90%


01:01:08.700 --> 01:01:10.364 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:10.364 --> 01:01:17.100 align:middle line:84%
Now I want to give one
application of this.

01:01:17.100 --> 01:01:18.840 align:middle line:90%
And so this is the following.

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:41.700 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.700 --> 01:01:47.660 align:middle line:84%
So I now want to prove
the following corollary

01:01:47.660 --> 01:01:48.790 align:middle line:90%
of the Archimedean problem.

01:01:48.790 --> 01:01:53.540 align:middle line:90%


01:01:53.540 --> 01:01:56.620 align:middle line:84%
And the corollary
is that whenever

01:01:56.620 --> 01:02:01.730 align:middle line:84%
you have two real
numbers, x and y--

01:02:01.730 --> 01:02:04.090 align:middle line:90%
so these are real numbers.

01:02:04.090 --> 01:02:07.010 align:middle line:90%
And x here is less than y.

01:02:07.010 --> 01:02:26.130 align:middle line:84%
Then the claim is that then
there exists a rational number

01:02:26.130 --> 01:02:34.130 align:middle line:84%
m/n with the property
that is between these two

01:02:34.130 --> 01:02:42.770 align:middle line:84%
so that x is less than
m/n and less than 1.

01:02:42.770 --> 01:02:45.900 align:middle line:84%
that's what I want to prove
using the Archimedean property.

01:02:45.900 --> 01:02:49.690 align:middle line:90%


01:02:49.690 --> 01:03:04.480 align:middle line:84%
And so to prove
that, I look at beta.

01:03:04.480 --> 01:03:07.980 align:middle line:90%
Say beta is y minus x.

01:03:07.980 --> 01:03:11.240 align:middle line:90%


01:03:11.240 --> 01:03:13.400 align:middle line:90%
And I'm looking at--

01:03:13.400 --> 01:03:14.720 align:middle line:90%
so y minus x.

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:19.640 align:middle line:84%
Because y is bigger than
x, this here is positive.

01:03:19.640 --> 01:03:23.120 align:middle line:84%
And I can now look
at 1 over beta.

01:03:23.120 --> 01:03:28.600 align:middle line:84%
So 1 over beta is some
positive real number.

01:03:28.600 --> 01:03:31.940 align:middle line:84%
And now the Archimedean
property say that--

01:03:31.940 --> 01:03:50.520 align:middle line:84%
so by the Archimedean
property, there

01:03:50.520 --> 01:04:05.350 align:middle line:84%
exists a n, a natural
number such that n is

01:04:05.350 --> 01:04:08.290 align:middle line:90%
bigger than 1 over beta.

01:04:08.290 --> 01:04:10.990 align:middle line:90%


01:04:10.990 --> 01:04:12.710 align:middle line:90%
That's the Archimedean property.

01:04:12.710 --> 01:04:15.390 align:middle line:90%
It gives us this n.

01:04:15.390 --> 01:04:18.510 align:middle line:84%
But now, of course,
if that's the case,

01:04:18.510 --> 01:04:23.110 align:middle line:84%
this implies you can just
take 1 over it on both sides,

01:04:23.110 --> 01:04:25.470 align:middle line:84%
and that reverses
the inequality.

01:04:25.470 --> 01:04:31.810 align:middle line:84%
This implies that 1/n
is smaller than beta.

01:04:31.810 --> 01:04:32.730 align:middle line:90%
So we get that.

01:04:32.730 --> 01:04:35.950 align:middle line:90%


01:04:35.950 --> 01:04:41.300 align:middle line:90%
And so now we look at--

01:04:41.300 --> 01:04:49.070 align:middle line:90%


01:04:49.070 --> 01:04:54.430 align:middle line:84%
so now like define the
step size to some extent.

01:04:54.430 --> 01:05:00.570 align:middle line:84%
So we have here x,
and we have here y.

01:05:00.570 --> 01:05:05.790 align:middle line:84%
And beta is really
this distance here.

01:05:05.790 --> 01:05:10.970 align:middle line:84%
This here is beta, the
distance between the two.

01:05:10.970 --> 01:05:13.970 align:middle line:90%
And n here is--

01:05:13.970 --> 01:05:17.970 align:middle line:84%
we've now seen that there's an
n so that when you're looking

01:05:17.970 --> 01:05:21.570 align:middle line:90%
at 1/n, then--

01:05:21.570 --> 01:05:24.950 align:middle line:84%
so 1/n here is
smaller than beta.

01:05:24.950 --> 01:05:29.930 align:middle line:84%
It's something positive
and smaller than beta.

01:05:29.930 --> 01:05:33.590 align:middle line:90%
So now you're looking at the m.

01:05:33.590 --> 01:05:36.370 align:middle line:90%


01:05:36.370 --> 01:05:52.200 align:middle line:84%
So now look at the
integers so that m minus 1

01:05:52.200 --> 01:05:59.680 align:middle line:90%
is less than x times m.

01:05:59.680 --> 01:06:03.660 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you're looking
at this thing here.

01:06:03.660 --> 01:06:07.620 align:middle line:84%
If you take x times
n, this is an integer.

01:06:07.620 --> 01:06:11.760 align:middle line:84%
So there's definition
m with this property.

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:14.220 align:middle line:90%
And you can find the biggest--

01:06:14.220 --> 01:06:19.160 align:middle line:90%
so look at m with this property.

01:06:19.160 --> 01:06:31.240 align:middle line:84%
And let's denote n and choose
the largest one, the largest

01:06:31.240 --> 01:06:32.060 align:middle line:90%
such m.

01:06:32.060 --> 01:06:38.960 align:middle line:90%


01:06:38.960 --> 01:06:45.980 align:middle line:84%
So if you choose the largest
such m, then you see that--

01:06:45.980 --> 01:06:48.630 align:middle line:84%
so this inequality
here, this will just

01:06:48.630 --> 01:06:58.690 align:middle line:84%
tell you that m minus 1 over
n, that this is smaller than x.

01:06:58.690 --> 01:07:02.830 align:middle line:90%


01:07:02.830 --> 01:07:05.950 align:middle line:84%
But you would also
have that because it

01:07:05.950 --> 01:07:07.670 align:middle line:90%
was the largest such m--

01:07:07.670 --> 01:07:11.150 align:middle line:90%


01:07:11.150 --> 01:07:26.510 align:middle line:84%
since m was the
largest such m, then

01:07:26.510 --> 01:07:32.590 align:middle line:84%
you would have that if you had
m itself in the denominator,

01:07:32.590 --> 01:07:35.210 align:middle line:84%
then it wouldn't
be smaller than x.

01:07:35.210 --> 01:07:37.830 align:middle line:84%
It would actually be
larger or equal to x.

01:07:37.830 --> 01:07:40.710 align:middle line:90%


01:07:40.710 --> 01:07:44.790 align:middle line:84%
And I just want to now
prove that this-- so this

01:07:44.790 --> 01:07:46.590 align:middle line:90%
here is bigger than x.

01:07:46.590 --> 01:07:48.970 align:middle line:84%
That's part of what
I needed to prove.

01:07:48.970 --> 01:07:51.870 align:middle line:84%
I also wanted to show
that it's smaller than y.

01:07:51.870 --> 01:07:58.170 align:middle line:90%


01:07:58.170 --> 01:08:01.530 align:middle line:90%
But if you now add--

01:08:01.530 --> 01:08:02.910 align:middle line:90%
but now the step size.

01:08:02.910 --> 01:08:05.330 align:middle line:90%
So when you have here--

01:08:05.330 --> 01:08:07.330 align:middle line:90%
here, you have x.

01:08:07.330 --> 01:08:08.386 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have y.

01:08:08.386 --> 01:08:11.130 align:middle line:90%


01:08:11.130 --> 01:08:14.390 align:middle line:84%
1/n was smaller
than this distance.

01:08:14.390 --> 01:08:16.649 align:middle line:84%
So if you are at
some point here--

01:08:16.649 --> 01:08:21.330 align:middle line:84%
this is where you are when
you are at n minus 1/n.

01:08:21.330 --> 01:08:24.270 align:middle line:84%
Then you can't go
further to the right.

01:08:24.270 --> 01:08:28.750 align:middle line:90%
You go 1/n to the right.

01:08:28.750 --> 01:08:32.729 align:middle line:84%
But that can't take
you all the way past y.

01:08:32.729 --> 01:08:37.609 align:middle line:84%
So that's why, if you're
looking at this number here,

01:08:37.609 --> 01:08:42.450 align:middle line:90%
this m must be smaller than y.

01:08:42.450 --> 01:08:45.800 align:middle line:84%
And if I had just chosen
m so that this here

01:08:45.800 --> 01:08:48.000 align:middle line:84%
was smaller or equal
to that, then I

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:50.800 align:middle line:90%
would get this [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:50.800 --> 01:08:51.652 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:51.652 --> 01:08:56.899 align:middle line:84%
So that's a corollary of
the Archimedean property.

01:08:56.899 --> 01:08:59.880 align:middle line:84%
I think there would be
something along these lines

01:08:59.880 --> 01:09:01.200 align:middle line:90%
on the homework.

01:09:01.200 --> 01:09:05.080 align:middle line:84%
And again, I'm just waiting
for the office hour.

01:09:05.080 --> 01:09:07.080 align:middle line:84%
I know that the office
hour, there will at least

01:09:07.080 --> 01:09:11.000 align:middle line:90%
be four office hours next week.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:15.399 align:middle line:84%
On Mondays and Wednesday, there
would be office hours from 5:00

01:09:15.399 --> 01:09:20.319 align:middle line:90%
to 6:00 on Monday and Wednesday.

01:09:20.319 --> 01:09:25.340 align:middle line:84%
And the other days, it
would be 1:15 to 2:15.

01:09:25.340 --> 01:09:30.560 align:middle line:84%
But you can check-- the time
is actually already posted.

01:09:30.560 --> 01:09:33.000 align:middle line:84%
The room number, I hope
to have that today.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:35.680 align:middle line:84%
Once I have that,
then I will also

01:09:35.680 --> 01:09:39.319 align:middle line:84%
assign the homework, probably
today, or maybe more likely,

01:09:39.319 --> 01:09:40.859 align:middle line:90%
tomorrow, the homework.

01:09:40.859 --> 01:09:46.550 align:middle line:84%
But it won't be due next
week, just the following week.

01:09:46.550 --> 01:09:47.729 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

01:09:47.729 --> 01:09:50.310 align:middle line:90%


01:09:50.310 --> 01:09:52.109 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, I
very much encourage

01:09:52.109 --> 01:09:56.070 align:middle line:90%
you to go to the office hours.

01:09:56.070 --> 01:09:59.490 align:middle line:90%
And yeah.

01:09:59.490 --> 01:09:59.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:09:59.990 --> 01:10:01.350 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Are you
upper bounding--

01:10:01.350 --> 01:10:01.890 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Sorry.

01:10:01.890 --> 01:10:02.682 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Oh, sorry.

01:10:02.682 --> 01:10:03.310 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Oh.

01:10:03.310 --> 01:10:06.950 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So we defined
plus in the solution.

01:10:06.950 --> 01:10:11.110 align:middle line:84%
So how do we define
minus 1, for example?

01:10:11.110 --> 01:10:12.990 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So remember
that the minus 1

01:10:12.990 --> 01:10:18.750 align:middle line:84%
was this element that
you had when you had--

01:10:18.750 --> 01:10:22.310 align:middle line:84%
remember that a field had
the two operation, plus

01:10:22.310 --> 01:10:23.650 align:middle line:90%
and multiplication.

01:10:23.650 --> 01:10:27.610 align:middle line:84%
And for each of these
that had 5 property,

01:10:27.610 --> 01:10:32.670 align:middle line:84%
they were almost
the same property.

01:10:32.670 --> 01:10:35.390 align:middle line:84%
There was one exception,
that 0 didn't have

01:10:35.390 --> 01:10:37.830 align:middle line:90%
a inverse for multiplication.

01:10:37.830 --> 01:10:40.510 align:middle line:90%
But minus 1 is the--

01:10:40.510 --> 01:10:43.570 align:middle line:84%
so you have 1, but 1
is the neutral element

01:10:43.570 --> 01:10:45.410 align:middle line:90%
for multiplication.

01:10:45.410 --> 01:10:45.910 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:10:45.910 --> 01:10:48.290 align:middle line:84%
That was how 1 was
defined, right?

01:10:48.290 --> 01:10:52.290 align:middle line:84%
And we proved that
there was a unique 0.

01:10:52.290 --> 01:10:56.450 align:middle line:84%
That same argument would
prove that there's a unique 1.

01:10:56.450 --> 01:10:58.890 align:middle line:90%
So there's just one 1.

01:10:58.890 --> 01:11:01.410 align:middle line:90%
So it's a well-defined notion.

01:11:01.410 --> 01:11:04.730 align:middle line:84%
And then you can look at
the inverse element of that

01:11:04.730 --> 01:11:06.390 align:middle line:90%
with respect to addition.

01:11:06.390 --> 01:11:09.710 align:middle line:90%
That's minus 1.

01:11:09.710 --> 01:11:10.210 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:11:10.210 --> 01:11:12.568 align:middle line:90%


01:11:12.568 --> 01:11:14.610 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Why did we define
an upper bound and not

01:11:14.610 --> 01:11:15.570 align:middle line:90%
a lower bound?

01:11:15.570 --> 01:11:17.670 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, and
that's a good question.

01:11:17.670 --> 01:11:20.510 align:middle line:84%
And I will come back
to that next time.

01:11:20.510 --> 01:11:25.210 align:middle line:84%
And it would seem more
logical to define both upper

01:11:25.210 --> 01:11:26.390 align:middle line:90%
and lower bound.

01:11:26.390 --> 01:11:30.290 align:middle line:84%
But you can look
at the complement.

01:11:30.290 --> 01:11:33.130 align:middle line:84%
And so if you take
a set and you're

01:11:33.130 --> 01:11:36.330 align:middle line:84%
looking at the complement,
then the upper bound for that

01:11:36.330 --> 01:11:38.080 align:middle line:90%
is the same as the lower bound.

01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:40.420 align:middle line:90%
So that's a kind of sneaky way--

01:11:40.420 --> 01:11:44.270 align:middle line:90%
that's the reason why we did it.

01:11:44.270 --> 01:11:46.500 align:middle line:84%
I might have done it
the other way around,

01:11:46.500 --> 01:11:49.180 align:middle line:84%
but then it was a
little bit overkill.

01:11:49.180 --> 01:11:52.780 align:middle line:84%
But I agree, it seemed more
logical to define both things.

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:54.700 align:middle line:84%
But it actually is
contained in this.

01:11:54.700 --> 01:11:57.280 align:middle line:90%


01:11:57.280 --> 01:11:59.640 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions?

01:11:59.640 --> 01:12:00.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:12:00.180 --> 01:12:02.555 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: I was a little confused
because I was thinking--

01:12:02.555 --> 01:12:05.040 align:middle line:84%
I wonder if you could please
speak about the completeness

01:12:05.040 --> 01:12:05.940 align:middle line:90%
of [INAUDIBLE]?

01:12:05.940 --> 01:12:16.520 align:middle line:84%
Like you make the
statement [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:16.520 --> 01:12:21.000 align:middle line:84%
say a bounded subset
of rational numbers

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:22.610 align:middle line:90%
would not have this upper bound.

01:12:22.610 --> 01:12:25.400 align:middle line:90%


01:12:25.400 --> 01:12:30.840 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So again, we
saw that square root of 2

01:12:30.840 --> 01:12:32.560 align:middle line:90%
is not a rational number.

01:12:32.560 --> 01:12:36.910 align:middle line:84%
And if we're looking at
all rational numbers,

01:12:36.910 --> 01:12:40.190 align:middle line:84%
all rational numbers
so that the square is

01:12:40.190 --> 01:12:45.950 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal
to 2, that set,

01:12:45.950 --> 01:12:48.530 align:middle line:84%
it has an upper bound
in the rational number,

01:12:48.530 --> 01:12:51.710 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't have
a least upper bound.

01:12:51.710 --> 01:12:53.990 align:middle line:84%
And that's because
we first prove

01:12:53.990 --> 01:12:59.310 align:middle line:84%
that there wasn't a rational
number so that it multiplied

01:12:59.310 --> 01:13:01.350 align:middle line:90%
itself was equal to 2.

01:13:01.350 --> 01:13:02.690 align:middle line:90%
We proved that--

01:13:02.690 --> 01:13:05.790 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: But does the least
[INAUDIBLE] also have to belong

01:13:05.790 --> 01:13:06.410 align:middle line:90%
to the--

01:13:06.410 --> 01:13:07.130 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's right.

01:13:07.130 --> 01:13:07.530 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:13:07.530 --> 01:13:07.830 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:13:07.830 --> 01:13:08.030 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: --[INAUDIBLE]?

01:13:08.030 --> 01:13:08.530 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:13:08.530 --> 01:13:08.970 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:13:08.970 --> 01:13:09.512 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:13:09.512 --> 01:13:10.210 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:13:10.210 --> 01:13:12.530 align:middle line:90%
So it's this.

01:13:12.530 --> 01:13:16.350 align:middle line:84%
A field is complete
means that whenever

01:13:16.350 --> 01:13:20.390 align:middle line:84%
you take a subset of that
field that is bounded,

01:13:20.390 --> 01:13:24.110 align:middle line:84%
then that subset has to
have a least upper bound.

01:13:24.110 --> 01:13:27.430 align:middle line:84%
But any bound, including
the least upper bound,

01:13:27.430 --> 01:13:28.980 align:middle line:84%
that always have to
be in the fields.

01:13:28.980 --> 01:13:31.590 align:middle line:90%


01:13:31.590 --> 01:13:32.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:32.210 --> 01:13:33.170 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions?

01:13:33.170 --> 01:13:34.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:13:34.180 --> 01:13:36.240 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Well, when
we tried to define it,

01:13:36.240 --> 01:13:42.300 align:middle line:84%
and [INAUDIBLE] did we also
prove the result 2 minus x

01:13:42.300 --> 01:13:46.900 align:middle line:84%
squared over 1 plus 2x is
smaller than 1 because you have

01:13:46.900 --> 01:13:51.400 align:middle line:84%
assumed for [INAUDIBLE] smaller
than 1 so that we can do the--

01:13:51.400 --> 01:13:56.980 align:middle line:90%


01:13:56.980 --> 01:13:59.452 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: So you're saying--

01:13:59.452 --> 01:14:01.160 align:middle line:84%
so I just want to make
sure I understand.

01:14:01.160 --> 01:14:05.900 align:middle line:84%
So in the step two,
we added something.

01:14:05.900 --> 01:14:09.100 align:middle line:84%
And we wanted to prove that
you could add something,

01:14:09.100 --> 01:14:11.240 align:middle line:90%
and this is still less than 2.

01:14:11.240 --> 01:14:13.924 align:middle line:90%


01:14:13.924 --> 01:14:20.660 align:middle line:84%
And so I was looking
for h between 0 and 1.

01:14:20.660 --> 01:14:24.620 align:middle line:84%
And so then I got some
equation somewhere

01:14:24.620 --> 01:14:26.460 align:middle line:90%
that is probably erased now.

01:14:26.460 --> 01:14:28.620 align:middle line:90%
But it just require that--

01:14:28.620 --> 01:14:31.260 align:middle line:90%


01:14:31.260 --> 01:14:34.873 align:middle line:84%
h had to be positive, but
it was less than something.

01:14:34.873 --> 01:14:35.790 align:middle line:90%
And that was positive.

01:14:35.790 --> 01:14:37.332 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Yeah, but
that's something--

01:14:37.332 --> 01:14:40.360 align:middle line:84%
should the left
something smaller than 1?

01:14:40.360 --> 01:14:41.660 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:14:41.660 --> 01:14:42.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:42.160 --> 01:14:44.820 align:middle line:84%
So I don't remember
what I got here.

01:14:44.820 --> 01:14:48.100 align:middle line:90%
So yeah, you're right.

01:14:48.100 --> 01:14:50.020 align:middle line:90%
I guess I can reconstruct it.

01:14:50.020 --> 01:14:51.200 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Over 1 plus 2x.

01:14:51.200 --> 01:14:51.867 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:14:51.867 --> 01:14:54.960 align:middle line:90%


01:14:54.960 --> 01:14:59.880 align:middle line:90%
So what you are saying is that--

01:14:59.880 --> 01:15:02.080 align:middle line:84%
actually, so this
thing here is positive.

01:15:02.080 --> 01:15:05.920 align:middle line:84%
And so you want to choose
h so that it's smaller

01:15:05.920 --> 01:15:09.400 align:middle line:90%
than this but also this here.

01:15:09.400 --> 01:15:11.000 align:middle line:90%
So you don't.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:17.640 align:middle line:84%
But if this is
500, well, I'm not

01:15:17.640 --> 01:15:20.900 align:middle line:84%
going to choose 500 because it
was supposed to be less than 1.

01:15:20.900 --> 01:15:23.640 align:middle line:84%
But I just choose it so
that it's less than 1

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:25.780 align:middle line:84%
and also less than
this positive number.

01:15:25.780 --> 01:15:27.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:15:27.290 --> 01:15:31.000 align:middle line:90%